00:49:11.004 --> 00:49:30.593
Incoming livestream: rock curves, area under rock, area under precision recall. All of this assumes, that we have access to transparent labels, and we're operating in an environment, in which, the truth is ascertainable. Of course, in cybersecurity, this just isn't the case. That's not the kind of discipline, that we are. That's not the kind of domain in which we're operating.


316
00:49:30.594 --> 00:49:52.064
Incoming livestream: with respect to program security, an AI system may propose a patch to a critical program. How do we know if the patch works, right? All we really have, you know, we're up against sort of theoretical computer science problems, like the halting problem, and knowing whether it works, and so really we're using sort of heuristics to decide whether or not the patch works, like passes the unit tests, this sort of thing.


317
00:49:52.144 --> 00:50:04.114
Incoming livestream: Like, what's malware? You know, and is a program malware? Right, we're up against these same kind of theoretical problems, and also more sort of ontological and epistemological problems of, like, you know, the fact that many binaries are actually dual use.


318
00:50:05.784 --> 00:50:23.673
Incoming livestream: And, okay, so, actually, so in my experience actually building, autonomous systems for AI security, I've come up against this problem in many practical settings. So, for example, has anybody here actually tried to get ground truth and train a system to, follow up on alerts in the SOC?


