00:50:49.894 --> 00:50:52.974
Incoming livestream: You're gonna see a ton of noise in those labels.


321
00:50:53.704 --> 00:50:59.853
Incoming livestream: If you're trying to build a system that automates access management, and you want to know.


322
00:50:59.874 --> 00:51:24.873
Incoming livestream: who should really have access to that sensitive database table that has user messages in it, for example. You'll find that access investigators will disagree at a double-digit rate, right, with respect to who should actually access what. So if you're trying to train a machine learning system or evaluate its ability to automatically grant or deny access, you're dealing with a ton of noise in your labels, which makes the evaluation problem very different than the problem of evaluating a computer system, computer vision system that decides


323
00:51:24.874 --> 00:51:25.934
Incoming livestream: Cat versus dog.


324
00:51:27.144 --> 00:51:33.604
Incoming livestream: So I actually ran a little simulation for you guys, to sort of try to demonstrate this concept.


325
00:51:33.604 --> 00:51:50.243
Incoming livestream: So if you… so you should sort of track me down after this, and I can tell you all the parameters of the simulation, but basically, if you add, like, a 1% flip rate, where you're flipping true positive to false positive and false positive to true positive, and your labeled data with which you're using to evaluate your machine learning system.


326
00:51:50.244 --> 00:52:04.894
Incoming livestream: Your ability to measure whether or not your system actually works just plummets as you add noise. So in this simulation, I'm imagining you have, like, a sort of perfect AI system that predicts, for example, whether or not a SOC alert is a false positive.


327
00:52:04.894 --> 00:52:21.584
Incoming livestream: And as we add noise from, you know, 0.5% of the labels flipping to 3% of the labels flipping, what we observe is that the system starts to look really inaccurate, and we sort of start to hit a noise ceiling around… around… above which we can't actually measure the system's ability to improve.


328
00:52:22.604 --> 00:52:41.873
Incoming livestream: And I guess, I would say overall that the sort of bad news here is that all of this uncertainty is just built into the environment when you're trying to build autonomous cyber defense systems. So there are these theoretical computer science problems, like the halting problem and state space explosion that makes it impossible to know whether or not a program is bug-free, or whether or not a patch is gonna crash prod.


329
00:52:41.874 --> 00:52:50.923
Incoming livestream: There are these sort of societal problems of people disagreeing about whether or not a binary is really malicious or not, given many binaries are dual use.


330
00:52:50.924 --> 00:53:10.624
Incoming livestream: And we're not gonna… we're not gonna solve these problems, through more effort. We're always gonna be operating in this very uncertain environment, which, which begs the question, how are we gonna ship systems that we can rely on, which we can convince leaders of, which we can convince policymakers of, that can actually manage the cybersecurity of organizations autonomously?


331
00:53:12.704 --> 00:53:21.203
Incoming livestream: Okay, so I think the good news is that I think that our framing has been really wrong in how we evaluate, autonomous cyber defense systems.


