00:54:04.034 --> 00:54:22.474
Incoming livestream: But, you know, today, when we measure the precision recall F-score rock curve of a security machine learning classifier, we're assuming we have an oracle, right? So this is the sort of evaluation model that we're using in evaluating autonomous… evaluating cyber-autonomous defense systems right now. So we have sort of the ML system, which could be an AI agent.


336
00:54:22.474 --> 00:54:28.873
Incoming livestream: It's just a black box, we're not concerned about what's in the box. And what it's doing is it's saying whether


337
00:54:28.874 --> 00:54:36.913
Incoming livestream: A security alert is a true positive or a false positive. So it outputs just a series of ones and zeros, right? So we sort of reduced its behavior to this series…


338
00:54:36.914 --> 00:54:59.624
Incoming livestream: And then we have a set of labels. Now, the labels are actually totally noisy, and we can't trust them, right? The labels are like, you know, one SOC analyst who had a bad lunch, right, has decided that this alert was not investigation-worthy, right? So they're actually really noisy, but we assume that they are not noisy, right? And then we compute a bunch of summary statistics, which none of us actually trust very well in the field.


339
00:54:59.624 --> 00:55:03.693
Incoming livestream: And then we use those to present to our leadership and decide whether that system is worth deploying.


