00:55:09.884 --> 00:55:28.623
Incoming livestream: that had just generated 100,000 tokens of thinking and tool calling and explanation of its behavior and information retrieval, to finally produce a well-explained decision about whether a SOC alert was a false positive or true positive. And you reduced all that complexity and reasoning down to a single bit of error information, right?


342
00:55:28.684 --> 00:55:36.894
Incoming livestream: So that's actually what we're often doing when we talk about evaluation of autonomous cyber defense systems. We're sort of reducing all that complexity down,


343
00:55:37.074 --> 00:55:41.214
Incoming livestream: To a single bit of information, which we don't actually, like, which we don't actually have a good label for.


344
00:55:42.384 --> 00:55:59.864
Incoming livestream: Imagine if we hired security engineers, on the basis of these kinds of binary, multiple-choice tests, and never interrogated their actual ability to reason under uncertainty. That's sort of what we're doing with AI systems, at least that's the sort of lingua franca in terms of how we talk about evaluation in our field.


345
00:56:01.654 --> 00:56:07.724
Incoming livestream: Okay, so here's the thesis of my talk. So I think these classical metrics that we typically use,


346
00:56:08.034 --> 00:56:16.283
Incoming livestream: I think they're important, I think we need them. I think we need to acknowledge and sort of bake in how noisy they are in how we evaluate our ML systems.


347
00:56:16.304 --> 00:56:40.263
Incoming livestream: But then I also think we need to really lean into understanding how our agents are reasoning and behaving, and evaluating that, also, as they make decisions. I think our mental model should be that when we hire a security engineer, we're hiring them to make good, well-validated decisions under the extreme uncertainty of our fields. And when we hire an AI agent, we're assessing their ability to do the same.


348
00:56:42.944 --> 00:56:54.463
Incoming livestream: Okay, so here's how, in my own work, I've, operationalized this, and love to hear feedback after this talk, just to hear if other folks are thinking in the same, in the same direction.


