00:56:57.834 --> 00:57:04.864
Incoming livestream: our agents, as we move to deploy them autonomously, as we would humans, who are deciding under uncertainty.


351
00:57:04.864 --> 00:57:18.504
Incoming livestream: So, we need to ask questions like, how high quality is the agent's reasoning process under complex, ambiguous circumstances? Did the agent come to the same conclusions as our best security engineers in the last 10 incidents? And if not, why not, and was the agent actually right? And actually.


352
00:57:18.504 --> 00:57:24.304
Incoming livestream: At least in my work, many times, we find that agents are actually right against human labelers.


353
00:57:25.374 --> 00:57:42.674
Incoming livestream: In a very practical and formal sense, what this means is that we need to define a kind of interview protocol, like a rubric for our agents. We need to define what good looks like, not just in terms of the outcome, but in terms of the process that they're taking to solve the highly ambiguous problems that we're gonna need our agents to solve. So, for example.


354
00:57:42.674 --> 00:58:05.423
Incoming livestream: did they, you know, let's say we're looking at agents in an access management setting, and we're asking, did they correctly grant access, you know, to a contractor, you know, with respect to a database table containing millions of user messages? We don't just want to ask, did they make the right decision? We also want to ask, did they gather the right evidence? Did they reason correctly from first principles about that evidence?


355
00:58:05.424 --> 00:58:20.724
Incoming livestream: Did they justify their decisions when explaining their decisions correctly? Did they explain clearly? Much like we'd be interviewing a human. And then we want to grade those agent trajectories at scale, based on the rubric and a very well-defined rubric protocol.


356
00:58:20.724 --> 00:58:30.434
Incoming livestream: And then because that doesn't scale, we need to train an AI system to actually automate that process of reviewing agent trajectories. And then once we deploy, we need to monitor.


357
00:58:30.644 --> 00:58:55.644
Incoming livestream: And see if the agent has gone off the rails. So here's sort of a worked example of applying this to an access management system, that monitors, granting access to sensitive resources within a company. We look at some… at criteria like evidence gathering, policy understanding, first principles, reasoning, whether the agent is sort of outputting logs in an auditable way, but also, finally, decision accuracy, also, but we… but it's a sort of whole…


358
00:58:55.644 --> 00:59:00.513
Incoming livestream: you know, what I'm arguing here is that we need a much more holistic approach than just looking at these summary statistics.


359
00:59:02.314 --> 00:59:17.264
Incoming livestream: You don't need a whole lot of samples to calibrate an LLM judge to do this sort of holistic, rubric-based analysis. Oftentimes, I mean, I don't have time to go into the details of the statistical model I'm using here, but oftentimes 100 samples is enough to get you started.


360
00:59:17.284 --> 00:59:41.624
Incoming livestream: And once you have the ability to judge, an AI agent's ability to reason and decide under uncertainty at scale, then it gives, then it gives your team a sort of hill to climb in terms of improving an agent to the point at which you can deploy it. So typically the process that I've found works is, like, you define some bar, above which we'll deploy an agent, that takes all these holistic dimensions into account.


361
00:59:41.684 --> 00:59:50.243
Incoming livestream: And then the team sort of hill climbs all of these criteria until we get above a bar and actually deploy the agent and sort of align that it's safe to deploy.


362
00:59:50.594 --> 00:59:54.134
Incoming livestream: And then once it's deployed, you sort of monitor it and make sure it's at steady state.


363
00:59:55.804 --> 01:00:04.683
Incoming livestream: So… I think, like, I just want to emphasize, at least in my work, this kind of approach has really unblocked a lot of progress.


